<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Sauvignon Blanc's Acidity to Cut Through Rich Dishes</strong> - Sauvignon Blanc's naturally high acidity (typically 6-7 g/L tartaric acid) makes it exceptional with fatty fish like salmon or tuna, creamy goat cheese, and herb-crusted dishes. The wine's citric acid content literally cuts through oils and fats, cleansing your palate between bites. This is why Loire Valley Sancerre pairs so beautifully with chèvre—both share the same terroir and complement each other perfectly.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve at 45-50°F to Preserve Aromatic Intensity</strong> - Unlike fuller whites, Sauvignon Blanc's volatile compounds (like 3-mercaptohexanol that creates grapefruit aromas) are best preserved at cooler temperatures. Serve straight from the refrigerator and keep chilled throughout the meal. Warmer temperatures above 55°F will mute the wine's signature herbaceous character and make food pairings less effective.</li>

  <li><strong>Skip the Decanter—Sauvignon Blanc Needs No Aeration</strong> - Sauvignon Blanc's appeal lies in its immediate aromatic impact from thiols and pyrazines. Decanting or excessive swirling actually diminishes these delicate compounds. Pour directly from bottle to glass to preserve the wine's fresh, grassy notes that make dishes like asparagus, peas, and fresh herbs sing.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Smaller Bowled Glasses to Concentrate Aromatics</strong> - Choose glasses with a narrower bowl than you'd use for Chardonnay—similar to a Riesling glass. This concentrates Sauvignon Blanc's volatile aromatics, enhancing your perception of the wine's herbal qualities that mirror ingredients like cilantro, basil, and green bell peppers in your dishes.</li>

  <li><strong>Pair Young Vintages with Delicate Preparations</strong> - Drink Sauvignon Blanc within 2-3 years of vintage when its primary fruit and herbal characteristics are most vibrant. These fresh flavors complement lighter preparations—think seared scallops with herbs, fresh salads, or crudo. Older bottles lose the bright acidity needed to balance delicate foods effectively.</li>

  <li><strong>Match Regional Styles to Complementary Cuisines</strong> - Grassy Loire Valley Sauvignon Blanc pairs with French herbs and goat cheese, while tropical New Zealand styles complement Asian cuisines with lemongrass and lime. Fumé Blanc's subtle oak works with slightly richer dishes like herb-roasted chicken. Understanding these regional characteristics helps you select the right style for your specific menu.</li>

  <li><strong>Exploit the Vegetal Character for Garden-Fresh Pairings</strong> - Sauvignon Blanc's pyrazine compounds create green bell pepper and grass flavors that make it the only wine that truly complements challenging vegetables like asparagus, artichokes, and Brussels sprouts. These typically wine-unfriendly foods become perfect matches when you embrace rather than fight the wine's herbaceous nature.</li>

  <li><strong>Time Your Opening for Peak Freshness During the Meal</strong> - Unlike wines that improve with breathing, Sauvignon Blanc is at its aromatic peak immediately after opening. Serve it with your first course or appetizers when your palate is most sensitive to its subtle herbal nuances. Its bright acidity also makes it an ideal aperitif wine to stimulate appetite before the meal begins.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What foods should I avoid pairing with Sauvignon Blanc?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Avoid heavy, rich dishes like braised short ribs, chocolate desserts, or heavily spiced Indian curries, as Sauvignon Blanc's bright acidity and herbaceous notes will clash with these bold flavors. The wine's citrusy character can also make already acidic foods like tomato-heavy pasta sauces taste overly tart. Instead, save your Sauvignon Blanc for lighter fare that complements its crisp, refreshing profile.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Does Loire Valley Sauvignon Blanc pair differently than New Zealand Sauvignon Blanc?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, significantly. Loire Valley Sancerre and Pouilly-Fumé are more mineral-driven and subtle, making them perfect with delicate seafood, fresh goat cheese, and herb-crusted fish. New Zealand Sauvignon Blanc, with its intense tropical fruit and grassy notes, pairs better with bolder flavors like Thai green curry, jalapeño-spiked dishes, or pesto pasta. The terroir creates completely different food pairing opportunities.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve Sauvignon Blanc for optimal food pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve Sauvignon Blanc at 45-50°F (7-10°C) for the best food pairing experience. Too cold, and you'll mute the wine's aromatic compounds that complement herbs and citrus in dishes. Too warm, and the alcohol becomes prominent, overwhelming delicate seafood and salads. At the proper temperature, the wine's acidity balances perfectly with rich ingredients like avocado or fresh mozzarella.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Sauvignon Blanc good for beginners learning food pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely – Sauvignon Blanc is one of the best wines for beginners to learn food pairing principles. Its pronounced acidity and distinct flavor profile make it easy to understand how wine interacts with food. You can clearly taste how its citrus notes enhance seafood, how its herbaceous quality complements green vegetables, and how its acidity cuts through rich sauces. The cause-and-effect relationship is much more obvious than with subtle wines like Pinot Grigio.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I pair aged Sauvignon Blanc with different foods than young versions?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, aged Sauvignon Blanc (3-5 years) develops honeyed notes and softer acidity, making it suitable for richer dishes like lobster with butter sauce or aged cheeses. Young Sauvignon Blanc's bright, grassy character pairs best with fresh herbs, raw preparations, and lighter proteins. Some premium Loire examples can age 10+ years, developing complex mineral notes that pair beautifully with truffle dishes or roasted poultry.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when pairing Sauvignon Blanc with food?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is pairing Sauvignon Blanc with overly sweet or heavily oak-aged dishes, which clash with the wine's crisp, dry character. Many people also serve it too cold, which masks the herbaceous notes that make it perfect with dishes containing cilantro, basil, or green bell peppers. Another error is choosing overly ripe, tropical-style Sauvignon Blancs for delicate seafood when a mineral-driven Loire style would be more appropriate.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I keep an opened bottle of Sauvignon Blanc for food pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">An opened bottle of Sauvignon Blanc maintains its food-pairing qualities for 3-5 days when properly stored with a vacuum seal in the refrigerator. After that, the wine's signature bright acidity and fresh aromatics begin to fade, making it less effective at cutting through rich foods or complementing herbs. For best pairing results, consume within 2-3 days when the wine's vibrant character is still intact.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's a good alternative if I can't find the right Sauvignon Blanc for my dish?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Albariño from Spain offers similar high acidity and citrus notes, making it excellent with seafood and herb-driven dishes. For dishes requiring Sauvignon Blanc's grassy, herbaceous character, try Grüner Veltliner from Austria, which has comparable green vegetal notes. Vermentino provides the mineral backbone found in Loire Sauvignon Blancs, while Vinho Verde offers the same palate-cleansing acidity perfect for rich or fried foods.</p>
